begin_memory_text: Introduced ourselves and figured out where we both live, Washington and New Jersey. Talked about the weather out in Washington although he thinks we are much colder than we really are.
middle_memory_text: We talked about working/not working. I asked him how the pandemic has changed his plans for the year, he mentioned he missed going to the movie theater but recently went to 3 movies. I asked the names of the movies and he told me a bit about them and the titles. We talked about being safe at the movie theater. Also chatted about air travel and whether or not any vacation plans had been interrupted.
end_memory_text: We moved into politics and the upcoming election. I asked him how the voting process worked in NJ, he told me he wasn't a registered voter. I then talked to him about how important voting can be at the local and state level, not just voting for president. He remained unconvinced and said he wasn't interested in registering to vote. We ended by disagreeing about whether or not Trump has done anything for our country.
rest_of_day_open: Work-wise it will be the same as it has been all year, my schedule will be normal. Online schooling will probably dominate my thoughts as I'm still helping my teenager adjust to a virtual school. I need to check in on his work every day to make sure he stays on track. I'm over a deadline on a special work project and will probably need to stay up late tonight to finish it up.
critical_positive: He listened closely and we had an even exchange of sharing conversation. He didn't hold back in bringing up potentially difficult topics and had not problem sharing his opinion on them. There were not noticeable lags in the conversation and we were able to keep it going without any difficulty.
critical_negative: This is the first conversation I've had where I didn't feel like I connected with the person very well. We did not have a lot in common and it felt like he was a bit disconnected from the world so my usual conversation topics weren't useful as I usually ask about work and family.

begin_memory_text: We talked about her experience with the wildfires in Washington state and how it affected her other family members.
middle_memory_text: We talked about how the pandemic affected us both personally and what we were doing to pass the time.  We would also talk about how serious the people in our community take the pandemic.
end_memory_text: We talked about voting and our desire to vote.  Then, I told her my case for not voting and if I did vote who I would probably lean toward voting for.
rest_of_day_open: I see myself watching a lot of tv possibly going to the movies and seeing a movie.  I might also rent a few redbox movies to pass the time.  Our family will definitely order takeout at least once in the week.  We may also go out to the park or beach to get some fresh air and exercise.
critical_positive: I would say that we both can relate to the pandemic personally because we are both dealing with it currently.  We both always had a topic we could talk about and not really have to struggle to have a conversion.  We both had a sense of humor and could joke around a little bit.
critical_negative: I would say sometimes there was a power struggle to control the conversion and voice oneâ€™s opinion or words over the other.  I think we had times where we had to make a little effort to find common interests at times.  For example, I knew more about movies and she knew about politics.
